Greenheart, Lenovo, Ping An, Sa Sa: Hong Kong Equities Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-09-27T01:02:51Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-27/greenheart-lenovo-ping-an-sa-sa-hong-kong-equities-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  fell 1.5 percent to 17,407.80. The Hang
Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, declined 3.3 percent to 8,735.40.  Chinese developers:  Shanghai ’s average home price was
15,190 yuan ($2,373) a square meter in the week ended Sept. 25,
according to Soufun Holdings Ltd. Property sales fell in 22 of
the 35 Chinese cities surveyed, the report said.  China Overseas Land & Investment Ltd. (688)  (688 HK), a developer
controlled by the nation’s construction ministry, gained 1.8
percent to HK$11.42.  China Resources Land Ltd. (1109)  (1109 HK), a
state-controlled developer, increased 0.9 percent to HK$8.90.  Guangzhou R&F Properties Co. (2777), the biggest developer
in the Southern Chinese city, tumbled 6.9 percent to HK$5.57.
The developer cuts its full-year sales target by 20 percent,
Hong Kong Economic Journal reported, citing Chairman Li Sze Lim.  Hong Kong developers: Hong Kong’s new mortgages drawn-down
fell 27 percent in August to HK$14.7 billion ($1.89 billion)
from July, according to a  statement  from the Hong Kong Monetary
Authority.  Sun Hung Kai Properties Ltd. (16)  (16 HK), the world’s biggest
developer by market value, fell 3.4 percent to HK$90.30.  Cheung Kong  (Holdings) Ltd. (1 HK), controlled by
billionaire  Li Ka-shing , retreated 2.4 percent to HK$86.45.  Retailers: Hong Kong’s visitor arrivals from mainland China
may increase by as much as 10 percent during the Chinese
National Day holiday week starting Oct. 1, James Tien, chairman
of Hong Kong Tourism Board, said in an e-mailed release.  Sa Sa International Holdings Ltd. (178)  (178 HK), Hong Kong’s
biggest listed cosmetics retailer by market value, sank 8.2
percent to HK$4.13.  Hengdeli Holdings Ltd. (3389)  (3389 HK), the retail
partner of Swatch Group AG in China, retreated 1.4 percent to
HK$2.83.  Emperor Watch & Jewellery Ltd. (887)  (887 HK), a Hong Kong-
based retailer of luxury watches and jewelry, tumbled 17 percent
to HK$1.01.  Greenheart Group Ltd. (94 HK): The unit of tree-plantation
operator Sino-Forest Corp. applied to resume trading in Hong
Kong today after giving more details about its operations in
Suriname and its ties to the parent. Hong Kong’s Securities and
Futures Commission ordered the Hong Kong exchange to suspend the
shares on Aug. 29 after it raised questions about the expiry of
a logging license in Suriname, it said.  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China (601398)  Ltd. (1398 HK): The
nation’s biggest lender by market value said its board had
approved a plan to sell as much as 70 billion yuan in
subordinated debt with a maturity of no less than five years.
The shares fell 2.8 percent to HK$3.85.  Lenovo Group Ltd. (992)  (992 HK): The maker of personal computers
said it agreed to set up a production venture with Compal
Electronics Inc. (2324 TT). Separately, Lenovo asked MediaTek
Inc. (2454 TT) to increase chip production to meet demand for
its smartphone A60 before China’s national holidays, the
Commercial Times reported, without saying where it got the
information. Lenovo sank 5.9 percent to HK$4.46.  Ping An Insurance Group Co. (2318 HK): China’s second-
biggest insurance company by market value said its main
shareholders haven’t reduced their stakes and have no plans to
do so. The insurer doesn’t have any new fund-raising plans and
hasn’t invested in European bonds, according to the company’s
Shenzhen-based spokesman Sheng Ruisheng. The shares tumbled 14
percent to HK$42.50.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in  Hong Kong  at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 